This repository contains a practical implementation of the first lab from the 
MIT Introduction to Deep Learning course, focusing on the fundamental building 
blocks of PyTorch. The notebook demonstrates how to create and manipulate 
tensors of various dimensions—ranging from 0D scalars to 4D tensors used in 
image processing—and how to perform slicing and mathematical operations 
within computational graphs. 

It explores building neural networks by subclassing `torch.nn.Module`, 
illustrating both custom parameter initialization for a basic dense layer 
and the use of built-in components like `nn.Linear` with Sigmoid activations. 
Additionally, the project covers the implementation of flexible forward 
passes that can alter network behavior dynamically during execution. 

Finally, it provides a hands-on introduction to automatic differentiation 
using PyTorch's Autograd engine (`requires_grad` and `.backward()`) and 
applies it to optimize a simple loss function via Gradient Descent, 
visualizing the optimization process and convergence using Matplotlib.
